<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-01-31T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-01-31T09:00:00-05:00" n="605" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d605">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/8050:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Morris</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-01-31T16:00:00+02:00">January 31, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received February 1—3:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>354. In the course of my visit of condolence over the death of
                                General Metaxas<note n="14a" xml:id="d605fn14a">General Metaxas died
                                    January 29, 1941.</note> the Greek Minister here informed me
                                that German officials, both military and civil, were utilizing every
                                opportunity and contact to assert to him the precarious situation of
                                Greece, specifically <pb facs="0654" n="642" xml:id="pg_642"/>
                                alleging that American help would not be forthcoming in time to be
                                effective and that American planes and other armament were inferior
                                to German.</p>
                            <p>The German officials had not, I understand, gone so far in their
                                representations to him as to suggest that the Greek Government
                                endeavor to make peace with Italy but it was obvious that they hoped
                                he would believe and repeat to Athens these defeatist ideas.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>